review_blob: Strait forward good balance some musk Mellon and not too sweet . Very drinkable.

Pour is a light yellow, good lacing. Nose is tart. Mouthful is light without being watery, cotes the mouth reasonable well. Taste is simple, a little grainy a little lemon. Dryer then most lager imports. A nice light beer.

Had this on tap. Clear with a medium head. Smells of grass, citrus and bannana. Taste crisp mildly sweet. Grain and grass come through on chewing. Medium carbonation which a decent mouth feel. A good example of wheat.
Had this on tap, little head, clear golden with no lacing. Heavy yeast taste, with lots of banana and bubblegum. Alcohol comes through too much.

750ml bottle no 05571 2009-1. Pour is light golden with a perfect, yes a perfect head. The head is creamy long lasting with lots and lacing. It has those champagne like bubbles and is simple beautiful; and yes pour this very carefully and very slowly.  Smells slightly sweet with a little grass and a mild Brett smell. Feels lite as those delightful bubbles massage the tongue. Taste is a balance of sweet and bitter and just a hint of sour. Crewing brings our citrus, banana and bubble gum esters, and slight bitter sour cherries. This is not big anything, it is a wonderful balance. A great summer beer I hope I can find more.

Nose is sweet and sugary. Malt smell earthy. Pour is clear dark brown/mahogany some head and large carbonation. Feel is light and fresh with a surprising amount of carbonation on the tongue.  Taste likes hops This is a surprise. Bigger than I would expect for this style but good. Sharp spicy bitter. Long bitter finish. Tasting brings out citrus, and floral.

Had not intended  opening this  on such a bright a sunny day. I bumped it when shifting stuff  and when the cap started hissing, I knew that I had no choice.  Pour is clear dark reddish-brown with a dense rich tan head. Nose is ginger, molasses and the unmistakable floral hops. Initial sip is rich and coats the mouth and the teeth evenly. Slight sweetness which immediately turns to bitter. As I swallow the bitter subsides again revealing the sweet with bitter finishes.   Rolling it around brings out a slight sourness. Rolling it also brings out tar and tobacco.  A big beer which I think would have been better on a winter day. Good but I generally like a little better balance, not quit such a tug of war.

Had this on tap at Vine Street Pub. Pour was a crystal clear golden with a disappointing tan head. Nose was strongly of musk melon and honey. Obvious grass and grapefruit as well.  Tasting it brought out bubblegum and a little caramel. Not unexpectedly it had a sharp bitter finish with an equally not surprising sweetness. The alcohol came through more then I like but it was not over whelming, very good for 11%.  Low carbonation and thick feel. An extremely drinkable beer, with a great nose and a delightful taste but maybe, just maybe a little overrated.

Pour is dark brown with reddish tinge.  Mild head which settle with some lacing.  Nose is sour  (definitely reminds me of the crab apples rotting on the ground after falling off my parents tree) with some wood (cedar?). Taste is equally sour and bitter. Medium feel fills the mouth. Hoppy finish is dry on the tongue.

Pour is a dense creamy head with holds for a moderate time. Settles with little lacing.  Beer is clear and very dark brown.  Nose is rich caramel. Slightly smoky, dark chocolate, slight apple and rose.  Taste is slightly tart, slightly metallic with a moderately bitter finish.  Feel is light and full. A great beer.

Pour is a cloudy dark copper with a thin short head (should be moussy). Smells of banana, with some spice and bubble gum. Initially a little fishy.  Basically true to style. Taste is slightly sweet with the bubble gum coming though a bit more as you roll it. Slight citrus tartness with a bitter hop finish.  Palate is soft with a strange body. It seems to be a nice medium but at the same time a little watery. Not my favorite style but a good beer.

Pour from a 12oz. dense head and a dark amber color.  Nose is dominated by caramel, resin and pine with faint rose floral quality.  Taste is extremely sweet like a candy with a bitter finish. Some anise and oak. Taste is not well  balanced though reasonable complex. Feel is smooth with a light carbonation. Coats well and rolling it brings out a bourbon taste.

Pour is dark amber with a quick settling big bubbled head. Some lacing. A rich malty nose. Spice and chocolate and nut. A nice full feel (only 5.8% ABV?) with moderate carbonation. Taste of malt and hops and is nicely balanced.

Pour is pale straw with a think head.  Nose is complex containing, lemon, orange peel, spice, cloves, ginger and of course hint of the brett. Sourness is complemented by a slight sweetness. Feel is medium body and a tingle moderate to low carbonation.  Finish is of honey. I like this beer. I really like this beer.
This yellow to orange pour looks and full mouth as it feels. Nose is all pine and grapefruit. A rich hoppy flavor with a hint of sweetness in the form of caramel.  A satisfying beer.
Pour is a straw. Nose is some bubblegum but mostly vegetables and corn. Feel is light and delicate.

Pour is golden and clear with a quick settling golden head. True to style. Nose is yeast and toast; little fruit; and some pepper.  Taste is slightly sweet. Grain comes though. Some mild hops and mild alcohol flavor. Mouth feel is moderate with moderate carbonation. A fine though not outstanding beer.

Pour is a cloudy straw with a robust white head, which is dense soft and very long lasting. Prodigious lacing. Nose is sweet, with notes of honey, coriander, and citrus (orange, and lemon). Taste is spicy, yeasty, and a touch hot. A moderate hoppy bitterness is right on. Feel is medium body with great coating.

A dark straw with a big bubbled white head. Settles quickly. Smells of orange and slight floral hops. Taste is a nice balance of sweet and dry. Lasting dry finish with hints of tartness. Crisp in the mouth.
Pour a yellow with a green twinge. Small light white head. Smells lightly of citrus. Taste is of grain with a even bitter sweet flavor. Soft feel and moderate carbonation.

Pour is crystal clear straw with a rich white head. Some head retention with good lacing.  Slight floral nose which is dominated by corn. Tasting bring out more grain. Slight sweet malt taste which lingers throughout immediately followed by a bitter sweetness with a long dry finish.

Rich dark pour with a billowy dark long lasting tan head. Smells of molasses ginger, cinnamon, tar and tobacco.   Taste is sweet with a moderately smoky bittersweet finish. Tasting also brings our dried fruit primarily plumes and cherries.  Feel is soft, with little carbonation. Goes down very smoothly.

Pour is clear golden with a light tan creamy head. Settles quickly leaving some lacing. Smells of lemon, pineapple and pine.  Taste is slightly sweet and brings out a corny quality. A pleasant mild dry finish. Feels is a little thin. A drinkable light beer.

Pour is deep reddish brown, with a very dense pinkish tan head. Moderate lacing. Nose of caremel, apple, cider vinegar. Taste is slightly sour, sweet malt, apple, some lemon and rose water. Moderate carbonation with a smooth mouth feel.
UPDATED: SEP 21, 2009

Shared a 750 with Dr Jay, pour is dark with a rich brown head and good lacing. Smells of tar, and tobacco, pine, chocolate and soy sauce. A rich nose for a rich beer. The taste is slightly sweet with a liquid smoe quality. Some prune,coffee and molasses. Feel is light but not watery.
beer_name: Left Hand SmokeJumper Imperial Smoked Porter

review_blob: LIght and fresh. A straw color with a creamy white head. Mild lacing. Mild yeast, honey, chamomile,  Taste is even a little sweet a little sour and a little bitter. This is soft and goes down very easily.

Pour is dark golden with a very rich creamy tan head.  Nose is strongly pine and muskmelon. Tasting it brings out honey and vanilla. This is a light malty sweetness with a hoppy bitterness that is less than the nose suggest however not too little my any measure. Soft beer coats well with a gentle carbonation a has a slight thin feel.
Pour is light golden with white head. Bottles smells of yeast. Nose in the glass is a faint orange. This is  a spicy beer, lots of pepper and clove.  Feel is smooth, and soft with nice carbonation.
Pour is light straw with a thick white head. Head settles slowly with little lacing. Bottle smells strongly of yeast &#

Pour from a 22 is hazy pale yellow with a white head. Moderately slow to settle with some lacing. Smell is mostly of yeast, with some lemon and melon and a little coriander.  Some aftertaste of anise. Taste is sour with a hint of sweetness and a bitter finish which lingers. Feel is moderate but not watery.  Not complicated but good.

Pour is clear dark amber with a soft head that settles quickly. Smells earthy, yeasty like a wet bread dough. Some malty fruit perhaps overripe cherry. Tasting it brings out more floral notes and a slightly metallic quality.  It leaves a slight numbness on the palate. This is a rich beer with a soft feel, a light sweetness and a quick dry finish.

Pour from a 25.4 is a clear pale straw with a big loose head. Head settles almost immediately leaving no lacing.  Smells of lemon, Belgium yeast and spice. Taste is mildly sour with light bitterness and slightly sweet finish. Refreshing. Feel is watery but leaves a noticeable coating. Nice fine carbonation.

Pour is light green with a white head. Settle with some lacing. Smells like fresh cut grass and lemon. Some spice. Mildly sweet and light sourness. Light and fresh on the pallet. a delightful summer beer.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Pour is crystal clear golden with an off white creamy head. Good retention good lacing.  Smells of pine resin, pineapple,  (guava?), pepper, spice maybe even a little cinnamon. This beer is enormously complex. Taste is sweet and rich with a big bitter hoppy finish I have come to except from Port Brewing.  Coats the mouth well without leaving an oily residue. A terrific IPA.

Pour is darker straw with a tight white head, little to no lacing. Has a surprisingly outdoorsy smell, Yeast, grass, slight floral and citrus sent as if it were coming in on a breeze, a little dust. Really makes me think of summer.  Taste is initially a slight sweet sourness which gives away to a light bitter finish. Texture is odd in that some sips are watery and others have a nice full feel. A great summer beer!

Pour from a 750 is orangish amber with a soft white head. Smells of caramel, molasses, dried fruit, plumes, and spice. Just like Thanksgiving dessert! Sweet and soft on the pallete coat the mouth well and goes done easy. You can taste the alcohol some but it is not a distraction. Finish is thick and bitter with a slightly metallic quality.

Pour is deep mahogany with a rocky tan head that settles quickly. Smells of toffee, prunes and raisins. Taste is sweet but not as sweet as the nose would imply a mild bitterness lingers. As you aerating it in the mouth brings our subtle nut and a hint of cherry.  Palate is light with a slight gumminess on the back of the tongue; a surprising amount carbonation gives it a airy feel.

Pour is a hazy straw with fine carbonation and a long lasting white head. Smells of peach, apple, yeast, banana and spice. Taste is sweet slightly sour and finish with big bitterness. Though its the sweetness that lingers. Feel is thick and sticky.

Pour is glowing straw crystal straw with a big head which settle with no head. Smells slightly of apple and flowers and slight corky flavor. Crisp feel with a bright bitterness which lingers. This is refreshing and big, a terrific beer.

Pours a reddish amber, with a creamy tan head . Long lasting with good lacing.  Smells of big hops: pine, tobacco, licorice with toffee undertones. Taste is big with a gentle lingering bitterness. Feels thick and creamy with moderate carbonation.  This is a great beer.

Poured from a 12oz, this has a crystal clear amber color, a dense white head which settles quickly.  Smells of pineapple, apple, and spice. When chewed, a caramel sweetness comes though and is quickly replaced by a hoppy finish.  A clean crispness is a fresh feeling  with out being to light.
beer_name: Odell St. Lupulin Extra Pale Ale

review_blob: Shared a 500 with Jay. Pour is a medium amber with a white head. Smells of a malty sweetness with subtle fruit,( cherry, apple ) and spice against an earthy mushroom like background. A light feel with excites every taste bud on the tongue with a dry tannic grating sensation. Light sweetness is followed by a light bitter finish which quickly evaporates.

Shared a 12oz with Jay. This poured an amber with a white head. Subtle nose. Some malt taste the sweet wood comes though as well. A fair amount of spice, not really any detectable smoke flavor. mouth feel is initially thin but finishes smoother. A drinkable beer.

Shared a 12oz with Jay. Poured a straw color with a slight haze. Loose white head. Smells of peach, pear, and lemon. Some spice as well. Initial sweetness gives way to a tannic bitterness. Feel is too watery too much like club soda.

Shared this with Jay, A Clear dark straw color with a quick settling foamy white head. Smells like the essence of a sour apple (more wholesome than a Jolly Rancher but with a similar intensity). Sweet light with lots of carbonation as you role it around in your mouth.

Pour is light straw with a greenish tint. Head is White and foamy and settles quickly. Smells of bubble gum and exotic fruit. Taste is initially bitter followed by a sweet light fruit juice like quality and again with the bitter which evaporates to practically just a hint. Feels light with the slight tingle of a champagne like carbonation, coats well.

Medium gold pour with a creamy white head which quickly settles leaving lots of lacing.  Smells of pine, peach, some pear. Slight sour favor with predominate bitter hops. Dry floral finish with clove coming through. Crisp feel with a full body..
Pale straw pour with virtually no head. Smells of sour cherries and earth. Taste is the bitter somewhat sour earthly flavor of buckwheat. Alcohol is prevalent.
Pour is light yellow with a think head. Smells lightly of lemon and predominantly of smoked salmon. Taste is slightly sweet with a touch of sour. Feels fine, an interesting beer.
